academic or social readiness for kindergarten, but would she be socially mature enough to be with kids up to a year older when she hits the teenage years. Ultimately we chose to put her in early because she was ready and was already very mature for her age. In fact her kindergarten teacher was certain we put the wrong birth year and that she was actually five and a half. When I told her my daughter’s age, she was astonished and thanked us for sending her early. She is in grade 4 now, in a 4/5 spilt, and she is is still one if the most mature…. But she has been an old soul from the beginning. Lol &#10;All-in-all, you have to remember that what works for one child and family doesn’t necessarily work for another. If you put your child in kindergarten now and he isn’t ready for grade 1, have him repeat kindergarten. It wouldn’t be much different than having him repeat preschool now. Good luck! "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1206" language="en" documentId="5431" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Brandy" date="March 9, 2013 at 5:59 pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://blogs.babycenter.com/mom_stories/03072013-the-big-kindergarten-question-to-redshirt-or-not/comment-page-2/" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5431" notes="" title="The big kindergarten question: To redshirt or not?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="910"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="911" end="1206"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>